<h1 id="s1">1. Executive Summary</h1>
<div class="exec">
<p><b>What it is.</b> An AI agent that reads a customer/healthcare services contract (SOW/MSA/etc.) and produces a management-ready SLA risk &amp; negotiation dashboard — extracting the key SLA clauses, classifying and scoring risk, and recommending safer clause wording.</p>
<p><b>Built with Claude Code.</b> The agent, the analysis prompt, and the entire Node.js codebase were developed in Claude Code; at run time the app calls the Claude API to analyze each contract.</p>
<p><b>Value.</b> Cuts contract review from hours to ~10–15 minutes, applies one consistent standard to every contract, surfaces penalty/SLA exposure before signing, and produces a self-contained, downloadable report.</p>
<p><b>Why it's trustworthy.</b> Engineered against the two biggest AI risks — hallucination and prompt injection — with grounded extraction, evidence per finding, deterministic re-computation of critical facts, output validation, and enforced EM/pricing consistency. The same contract always yields the same result.</p>
</div>

<h1 id="s2">2. Objective &amp; Use Case</h1>
<table>
<tr><th style="width:22%">Field</th><th>Content</th></tr>
<tr><td><b>Use case</b></td><td>AI-Powered SLA Risk &amp; Negotiation Intelligence Agent</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Description</b></td><td>An AI agent that extracts key SLA clauses from SOWs, identifies potential risks, and generates actionable recommendations for better contract decisions.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Agent roles</b></td><td>SLA Risk Intelligence Agent &middot; Contract Review Agent &middot; Negotiation Recommendation Agent</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Primary users</b></td><td>Payers/health plans, providers/hospitals, MedTech &amp; Life Sciences, and healthcare-IT (SDLC) delivery, commercial, legal, and PMO teams.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Inputs</b></td><td>One contract file per run — PDF or DOCX, up to 25 MB (machine-readable text).</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Output</b></td><td>A single, self-contained, interactive HTML dashboard (7 sections), saved to history and downloadable.</td></tr>
</table>
<p><b>The problem.</b> Manual SLA review is slow, inconsistent between reviewers, and error-prone; unfavourable SLA commitments and penalty exposure are easy to miss and expensive to discover after signing.</p>

<h1 id="s3">3. Business Impact</h1>
<p>Directly addresses the stated business impact — prevents unfavourable SLA commitments, reduces penalty exposure, improves deal quality, accelerates review, and enables informed pre-deal decisions.</p>
<table>
<tr><th style="width:30%">Impact area</th><th>How the agent delivers it</th><th>Indicative metric</th></tr>
<tr><td>Accelerates review</td><td>AI first pass + human validation instead of full manual reading.</td><td>Hours &rarr; ~10–15 min per contract</td></tr>
<tr><td>Consistency / deal quality</td><td>Same rules on every contract; comparable across a portfolio.</td><td>100% reviewed to one standard</td></tr>
<tr><td>Prevents unfavourable SLAs</td><td>Key SLA Commitments table + risk scoring + recommended rewrites.</td><td>Every SLA target &amp; remedy surfaced</td></tr>
<tr><td>Reduces penalty exposure</td><td>Service-credit / penalty flagged and separated from value-at-risk.</td><td>Penalty clauses highlighted</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pre-deal decision-making</td><td>Management decision (Proceed / Conditions / Renegotiate / Do Not Proceed).</td><td>1 clear recommendation</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cost</td><td>AI cost tracked per run in the audit log.</td><td>~cents per contract</td></tr>
</table>
<p><b>Illustration.</b> A team reviewing ~200 contracts/year at ~3 hours each spends ~600 hours; at ~10–15 minutes of human validation on an AI first pass that drops to ~35–50 hours — roughly a <b>90% reduction in review effort</b>. <i>(Planning figures, not a guarantee.)</i></p>

<h1 id="s4">4. Definition of Done (DoD)</h1>
<p>The agent is "done" when it delivers all of the following:</p>
<ol>
<li>Extracts key SLA clauses (deliverables, availability, response time, resolution time, penalties).</li>
<li>Classifies SLA types.</li>
<li>Identifies potentially risky clauses using AI reasoning.</li>
<li>Highlights top risk areas with explanations.</li>
<li>Generates actionable recommendations and improved clause rewrites.</li>
<li>Produces a concise executive summary with overall contract risk indication.</li>
</ol>

<h1 id="s5">5. DoD Coverage — How We Meet Each Item</h1>
<p>Every DoD item is met. <span class="ok">✔ = delivered.</span></p>
<table>
<tr><th style="width:30%">DoD item</th><th style="width:8%">Status</th><th>Where in the solution</th></tr>
<tr><td>Extract key SLA clauses (deliverables, availability, response/resolution time, penalties)</td><td class="ok">✔</td><td><b>Key SLA Commitments</b> table (Executive Decision Brief) + <b>SLA Risk Assessment</b> ledger — Metric, Target, Measurement, Remedy/Penalty per clause.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Classify SLA types</td><td class="ok">✔</td><td><code>slaType</code> per row + <b>SLA / Clause Type Legend</b> (SLA/Service Level, Service Credit/Penalty, Termination/Step-in, Cost Impact, Security/Compliance, Governance/Evidence, Referenced Agreement).</td></tr>
<tr><td>Identify risky clauses via AI reasoning</td><td class="ok">✔</td><td>Each row carries Risk (High/Medium/Low), a Reasoning field, and a Confidence score.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Highlight top risk areas with explanations</td><td class="ok">✔</td><td><b>Top Risks</b> page + <b>Top decision blockers</b> — reason, evidence, recommended action.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Actionable recommendations + improved clause rewrites</td><td class="ok">✔</td><td><b>Recommendations &amp; Rewrites</b> page (original vs improved wording) + Management-ready Decision.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Concise executive summary + overall risk</td><td class="ok">✔</td><td><b>Executive Decision Brief</b> — Overall Risk KPI, Management Decision, 5-point Concise Management Summary.</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="ph">[ INSERT SCREENSHOT: Key SLA Commitments table (Executive Decision Brief) ]
<small>Shows SLA metric, target, measurement, remedy/penalty (colour-coded) and risk — the core DoD deliverable.</small></div>

<h1 id="s6">6. Over and Above the DoD</h1>
<p>Beyond the six DoD items, the solution adds substantial capability. <span class="extra">◆ = extra.</span></p>
<table>
<tr><th style="width:34%">Capability</th><th>What it adds</th></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Contract metadata extraction</td><td>Parties, dates, term, category, renewal, governing agreement, execution evidence — full Contract Overview.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ EM Level classification</td><td>Engagement model (EM 1 Staff Aug … EM 4 Fixed Price / Output+ / Outcome+) with inference basis.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Commercial Impact analysis</td><td>Value-at-risk, commercial baseline, revenue-protection controls, leakage scenarios, exposure model.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Priority (P1–P4) &amp; confidence</td><td>Incident-priority classification and a confidence score on every finding, with colour coding.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Page-level traceability</td><td>Deterministic page numbers derived from the evidence quote in the source text.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Management decision + risk chart</td><td>Proceed / Conditions / Renegotiate / Do Not Proceed, plus a donut chart of risk distribution &amp; value-at-risk.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ SLA benchmarking vs standard</td><td>Each extracted SLA is compared <b>in code</b> against an internal SLA/SOW/Project-Risk playbook — availability &amp; API/microservice uptime, incident response &amp; resolution by priority (P1–P4), latency &amp; error rate, defect/regression quality, service-desk metrics, security (breach notice, vulnerability remediation, RTO/RPO), delivery variances and penalty caps — and flagged Meets / Below standard / Uncapped, with a "SLAs below standard" count on the Executive Brief. So the tool <b>judges</b> the contract, not just extracts it. Deterministic, so it never hallucinates a verdict; vague targets are left for human review. A dedicated <b>Benchmark vs Standard</b> page presents the scorecard, the per-SLA verdicts, and the full house playbook (Supplier Safeguards, AI / LLM Usage &amp; Token Safeguards, and sections A–W including ARR/cloud-funding) as searchable, collapsible reference.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Determinism &amp; reproducibility</td><td>Temperature 0 + content-addressed cache — the same contract always yields the same report.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Guardrails</td><td>Input validation, prompt-injection/jailbreak screening, PII masking, output/schema validation, grounding checks, EM↔pricing consistency, rate limiting, access control, audit trail.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Multi-format &amp; multi-contract-type</td><td>PDF/DOCX; SOW/MSA/GSA/Order Form/Amendment/…; healthcare and general services contracts.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ History, dedup &amp; self-contained output</td><td>Analysis history, content de-duplication, and offline-openable HTML dashboards.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="extra">◆ Per-run output logs</td><td>A PII-masked log file is written to <code>output/logs/</code> on every analyze click (success, duplicate or error) — status, model, tokens, cost, page counts, injection/PHI flags and warnings — alongside the rolling <code>audit.log</code>, for full run traceability.</td></tr>
</table>

<h1 id="s7">7. How It Works — Architecture &amp; Pipeline</h1>

<h2>7.1 Processing pipeline</h2>
<table class="flowtbl">
<tr><td class="step"><b>1 · Upload</b> — user submits one contract file (PDF / DOCX).</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>2 · Validate</b> — file type, size (&le;25 MB), safe name; rate-limited. <span class="g">[Guardrail]</span></td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>3 · Extract</b> — PDF/DOCX &rarr; text; tag PDF pages with <code>[[PAGE n]]</code>; count pages.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>4 · Content dedup</b> — fingerprint the text; if already analyzed, point to the existing report. <span class="g">[Determinism]</span></td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>5 · Analyze</b> — hardened prompt + contract as untrusted data &rarr; Claude (temp 0) &rarr; JSON. Deterministic cache reused when available. <span class="g">[Injection defense]</span></td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>6 · Validate &amp; reconcile</b> — schema + enum checks (retry), EM↔pricing consistency, deterministic page numbers, grounding checks. <span class="g">[Anti-hallucination]</span></td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>7 · Build</b> — inject data into the fixed template; recompute counts; null fabricated money; add legends.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>8 · Save &amp; record</b> — write dashboard to <code>/output</code>, append history, write PII-masked audit line.</td></tr>
</table>
<p class="figcap">Figure 1 — End-to-end pipeline with the guardrail applied at each stage.</p>

<h2>7.2 Component architecture</h2>
<table class="arch">
<tr><td class="lane">Front end</td><td><code>index.html</code> (upload UI)</td><td><code>analysis-history.html</code> (history)</td><td>self-contained dashboard (output)</td></tr>
<tr><td class="lane">Server</td><td colspan="3"><code>server.js</code> — rate limit, validate, dedup, save, history API, audit, controlled static serving</td></tr>
<tr><td class="lane">Processing</td><td><code>extract.js</code> (PDF/DOCX + page tags)</td><td><code>analyze.js</code> (Claude, cache, retries, validation)</td><td><code>buildHtml.js</code> (assemble + reconcile)</td></tr>
<tr><td class="lane">Safety</td><td colspan="3"><code>guardrails.js</code> — validation, injection detection, PII masking, output/grounding/consistency checks</td></tr>
<tr><td class="lane">AI</td><td colspan="3"><code>analysis-prompt.txt</code> — instruction set + JSON schema (+ run-time hardening block) &rarr; Claude API</td></tr>
</table>
<p class="figcap">Figure 2 — Modules and layers (Node.js + Express; no heavy front-end framework).</p>

<div class="ph">[ OPTIONAL: replace Figures 1–2 with a polished diagram image if preferred ]</div>

<h2 id="s7c">7.3 File map &amp; data flow</h2>
<p>The application is deliberately small and modular — each file has one job, and data flows in one direction from upload to saved dashboard. The flow below names the file responsible at every step and what it produces.</p>
<table class="flowtbl">
<tr><td class="step"><b>index.html</b> — the user chooses one PDF/DOCX and clicks Analyze; the browser POSTs the file to <code>/analyze</code>.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>server.js</b> — receives the upload, rate-limits, validates it (via <code>guardrails.js</code>), then orchestrates every step below and returns the saved report path.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>extract.js</b> — turns the file into plain text; for PDFs it tags each page with <code>[[PAGE n]]</code> and returns the page count.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>server.js</b> — fingerprints the text (SHA-256) and checks history for a content or file-name duplicate; if found, it stops and points the user to the existing report.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>analyze.js</b> — reads <b>analysis-prompt.txt</b>, appends the <b>guardrails.js</b> hardening block, wraps the contract as untrusted data, and calls the <b>Claude API</b> (temperature 0). Returns validated JSON, reusing the deterministic <code>cache/</code> when the same contract was seen before.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>guardrails.js</b> — validates the JSON (schema/enums), reconciles page numbers from the evidence quotes, checks EM↔pricing consistency, and runs grounding/PHI checks.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>buildHtml.js</b> — normalizes the data (recomputes counts, nulls fabricated money, reconciles EM/pricing, adds the fixed legends) and injects it into <b>dashboard-template.html</b> at the data token.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="arr">&#9660;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="step"><b>server.js</b> — writes the finished dashboard to <code>output/</code>, appends a record to <code>output/history.json</code>, and writes a PII-masked line to <code>output/audit.log</code>.</td></tr>
</table>
<p class="figcap">Figure 3 — Which file does what, in order. <b>analysis-history.html</b> sits to the side: it reads <code>GET /api/history</code> to list every saved report.</p>

<table class="arch">
<tr><td class="lane">Input</td><td colspan="3">One contract file — <b>.pdf</b> or <b>.docx</b> (&le; 25 MB, machine-readable text)</td></tr>
<tr><td class="lane">Produced</td><td><code>output/&lt;client&gt;-&lt;file&gt;-analysis-&lt;timestamp&gt;.html</code> (the dashboard)</td><td><code>output/history.json</code> (index of reports)</td><td><code>output/audit.log</code> + <code>cache/&lt;hash&gt;.json</code></td></tr>
</table>
<p class="figcap">Figure 4 — What goes in, and the four things that come out.</p>

<h2 id="s7d">7.4 File-by-file reference</h2>
<p>Every file in the project, what it is for, why it is required, and what it covers.</p>
<table>
<tr><th style="width:20%">File</th><th style="width:30%">Purpose &amp; why it is required</th><th>What it contains / covers</th></tr>
<tr><td><code>index.html</code></td><td>The upload screen — the only page a user needs. Required as the entry point to the tool.</td><td>Branded upload card (indigo/purple/cyan), single-file picker restricted to PDF/DOCX, drag-and-drop guard, Analyze / Clear / View Analysis History buttons, progress state, duplicate-and-error popups, and the download of the finished dashboard.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>analysis-history.html</code></td><td>Lets the user find and reopen past analyses. Required so results persist and are reusable across sessions.</td><td>Calls <code>GET /api/history</code> and renders a table — Client Name, File Name, View, Download — plus a New Contract link back to the upload page.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>server.js</code></td><td>The Express coordinator — the backend that ties every module together. Required to receive uploads and run the pipeline safely.</td><td>Route handling (<code>/analyze</code>, <code>/api/history</code>, controlled static serving of the two pages and <code>/output/*.html</code> only), rate limiting, upload handling (Multer), content/name de-duplication, page-count injection, history persistence, PII-masked audit logging, a per-run output log file (<code>output/logs/</code>) written on every analyze click, and safe error responses.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>extract.js</code></td><td>Converts an uploaded file into the plain text the model reads. Required because the model cannot read binary PDF/DOCX directly.</td><td>PDF extraction via <code>pdf-parse</code> with a custom page renderer that inserts <code>[[PAGE n]]</code> markers and returns the page count; DOCX extraction via <code>mammoth</code>; whitespace normalization; rejection of scanned/empty files and legacy <code>.doc</code>.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>analysis-prompt.txt</code></td><td>The instruction set that turns Claude into a contract analyst. Required — it defines exactly what to extract and the JSON to return (explained in 7.5).</td><td>Grounding/anti-hallucination rules, extraction fields, status logic, page-citation rule, EM-level classification, EM↔pricing consistency, the risk ledger and SLA rows, the executive brief, commercial impact, recommendations, assumptions, and the full output JSON schema.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>analyze.js</code></td><td>Runs the prompt through the Claude API and returns clean, validated data. Required as the bridge between the prompt and the rest of the app.</td><td>Loads the prompt + hardening block, wraps the contract as untrusted data, calls Claude at temperature 0, auto-continues on truncation, retries transient errors with backoff, extracts and validates the JSON (one corrective retry), reconciles page numbers, runs the deterministic <code>cache/</code>, and returns run metadata (tokens, cost, warnings, PHI/injection flags).</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>guardrails.js</code></td><td>The central safety and quality module. Required to make the tool trustworthy — it defends against injection and hallucination and protects sensitive data.</td><td>Limits/constants, the system-hardening text, upload &amp; text validation, prompt-injection detection, untrusted-data wrapping, PII/secret masking and PHI detection (for logs/audit), output schema validation, grounding checks, EM↔pricing consistency checks, deterministic page reconciliation, and cost estimation.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>buildHtml.js</code></td><td>Assembles the final dashboard from the validated data. Required to guarantee a consistent, tamper-resistant output regardless of model wording.</td><td>Data normalization (recomputes risk counts, nulls fabricated money, reconciles EM/pricing trusting EM, derives contract status, snaps pricing labels), the SLA benchmark engine (compares each SLA to the fixed playbook and tags Meets / Below standard / Uncapped), the fixed legend definitions, colour-coding logic, and safe injection of the JSON into the template's data token.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>benchmark-reference.js</code></td><td>The full SLA/SOW/Project-Risk playbook (sections A–W + Supplier and AI/Token safeguards) shown as Reference Standards on the Benchmark vs Standard page. Kept separate because of its size; display-only reference, not auto-scored.</td><td>Grouped Category / Metric / Standard rows for every playbook section, the applicability matrix, derived metrics, and automated cross-checks.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>dashboard-template.html</code></td><td>The finalized visual design of the report. Required so the model never has to produce HTML — it only supplies data.</td><td>All eight pages, KPI cards, the contract strip, Management-ready Decision, Concise Management Summary, risk donut chart, Key SLA Commitments table, the full risk ledger, commercial-impact and recommendations pages, every legend, the Benchmark vs Standard page, and the CitiusTech-Confidential footer.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>package.json</code></td><td>Declares dependencies and the start script. Required for a clean, reproducible install.</td><td><code>express</code>, <code>multer</code>, <code>pdf-parse</code>, <code>mammoth</code>, <code>dotenv</code>, <code>@anthropic-ai/sdk</code>, and the <code>npm start</code> command.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>.env</code> / <code>.env.example</code></td><td>Holds configuration and the API key. Required to run; the key must never be committed.</td><td>Real secrets live only in the git-ignored <code>.env</code>; <code>.env.example</code> is the committed placeholder (API key, optional model, port, token/rate/pricing/cache settings).</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>.gitignore</code></td><td>Keeps secrets and generated files out of source control. Required for safe GitHub publishing.</td><td>Ignores <code>.env</code>, <code>node_modules/</code>, <code>output/</code>, and <code>cache/</code>.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>README.md</code></td><td>The single run-and-rebuild reference. Required so a judge can reproduce the result independently.</td><td>Prerequisites, install, commands, inputs/outputs, configuration, how it works, dashboard pages, architecture, security &amp; guardrails, GitHub key protection, and troubleshooting.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>output/</code></td><td>Where results and their trail live. Generated at run time (git-ignored).</td><td>The saved dashboard HTML files, <code>history.json</code> (report index + content fingerprints), and the PII-masked <code>audit.log</code>.</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>cache/</code></td><td>Guarantees determinism. Generated at run time (git-ignored).</td><td>One <code>&lt;sha256&gt;.json</code> per analyzed contract, keyed on contract text + prompt, so the same document always yields the same report.</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="s7e">7.5 The analysis prompt, explained section by section</h2>
<p><code>analysis-prompt.txt</code> is the heart of the agent. It never asks the model to write HTML — it asks for a single, strictly-shaped JSON object that the template renders. Each block below has a specific job.</p>
<table>
<tr><th style="width:26%">Prompt section</th><th>What it instructs, and why it matters</th></tr>
<tr><td><b>Role &amp; task framing</b> (opening lines)</td><td>Sets the job: read the uploaded contract and return the DATA (JSON) for a dashboard whose visuals are already fixed. Stops the model wasting effort — and drift — on styling or HTML.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>General rules</b> (grounding &amp; anti-hallucination)</td><td>The core safety contract: use only what is in the document; write "Not stated in uploaded contract" (or null) when a value is missing; never invent parties, dates, money, penalties or clauses; quote real text as evidence and score confidence honestly; be deterministic. Includes the PHI rule — this analyzes contracts, not patient records, so any patient identifiers are flagged in Assumptions, never reproduced.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Contract extraction</b></td><td>Lists the ~30 fields to pull (parties, dates, term, category, pricing, governing agreement, SLA/security/termination terms, execution evidence, …), the <code>DD-MMM-YYYY</code> date format, and the <b>status logic</b> (Upcoming / Active / On Hold / Expired / Not determinable) computed against the current date.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Page numbers &amp; citations</b></td><td>Tells the model to set each row's page only from the nearest preceding <code>[[PAGE n]]</code> marker, to keep citations out of text fields, and to make <code>evidence</code> a verbatim quote — because the app re-derives every page number by finding that quote in the source text. This is what makes page references trustworthy.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>EM level classification</b></td><td>Defines EM 1 (Staff Aug) through EM 4 (Fixed Price / Output+ / Outcome+) with explicit tie-breakers, and forbids defaulting to EM 4 just because a contract looks risky. Produces the engagement-model read that leadership cares about.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>EM ↔ pricing consistency</b></td><td>Maps each pricing model to its valid EM (T&amp;M &rarr; EM 1/2/3, never EM 4; fixed &rarr; EM 4 Fixed Price; output &rarr; Output+; outcome &rarr; Outcome+) and declares contradictions invalid. The app enforces this again in code, so the two can never disagree in the output.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Risk ledger</b></td><td>Builds one grounded row per obligation and, importantly, a dedicated <b>SLA row</b> for every service-level commitment with metric, target, measurement, remedy and cap — this is what feeds the Key SLA Commitments table. Fixes the risk vocabulary to High / Medium / Low and priority to P1–P4 with clear definitions.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Executive Decision Brief</b></td><td>Specifies the five KPI values, the overall-risk logic, the Management Decision enum (Proceed / Proceed with Conditions / Renegotiate / Do Not Proceed), the two decision boxes (proceed-if / renegotiate) as header+statement items, the five-bullet Concise Management Summary, and the risk chart rules.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Commercial impact</b></td><td>Asks for financial notes, a commercial baseline, revenue-protection controls, leakage scenarios and penalty exposure — while forbidding invented values and keeping Contract Value at Risk separate from service-credit exposure.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Recommendations &amp; rewrites</b></td><td>For each recommendation: risk level, contract area, recommended action, the original risky wording, and improved negotiation wording — only for clauses actually present in the contract.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Assumptions</b></td><td>Forces the model to state its own limitations — extraction gaps, unuploaded agreements, value treatment, confidence basis, page-number reliability, OCR needs — so the reader knows exactly how far to trust each figure.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Output format (JSON schema)</b></td><td>The exact object shape the app parses: <code>metadata</code>, <code>rows</code>, <code>counts</code>, <code>overall</code>, <code>boardDecision</code>, <code>bucketValues</code>, <code>boardSummary</code>, <code>decisionList</code>, <code>financialNotes</code>, <code>revenueControls</code>, <code>commercialBaseline</code>, <code>leakageScenarios</code>, <code>penaltyExposure</code>, <code>recos</code>, <code>assumptions</code>. Notes enforce the rules that matter: exclude legends (the app adds them), counts must equal the row totals, pricing/type labels are constrained, and only valid JSON with no control characters.</td></tr>
<tr><td><b>Run-time hardening block</b> (appended from <code>guardrails.js</code>)</td><td>Not stored in the file — <code>analyze.js</code> appends it to the system prompt at run time. It restates, at highest priority, that the contract between the <code>&lt;&lt;&lt;CONTRACT&gt;&gt;&gt;</code> markers is untrusted data to be analyzed, never obeyed, and that the instructions must never be revealed or changed. This is the primary prompt-injection defense.</td></tr>
</table>

