<h1 id="s9">9. Controls, Checks &amp; Validations</h1>
<p>Every stage is guarded. This is the core of the "well made / safe" evaluation.</p>
<table>
<tr><th style="width:26%">Control</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
<tr><td>Input validation</td><td>File type (PDF/DOCX only), 25 MB cap, safe file name (blocks path traversal/control chars), empty/scanned rejection.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Prompt-injection / jailbreak screening</td><td>Contract passed as untrusted data in <code>&lt;&lt;&lt;CONTRACT&gt;&gt;&gt;</code> markers; injection phrases detected and logged; system prompt protected.</td></tr>
<tr><td>PII / secret masking</td><td>Emails, phones, PAN, Aadhaar, API keys, passwords redacted from all logs and the audit trail.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Output &amp; schema validation</td><td>JSON schema + enum checks (risk, priority, overall, decision) with one corrective retry.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Anti-hallucination / grounding</td><td>Evidence per risk; counts recomputed from rows; fabricated money nulled; confidence + missing-evidence flags.</td></tr>
<tr><td>EM ↔ pricing consistency</td><td>Deterministically enforced (EM trusted, pricing corrected) so an impossible pair (e.g. T&amp;M + EM4) can never display.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Deterministic page numbers</td><td>Each page re-derived by locating the evidence quote in the page-marked source.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Determinism</td><td>Temperature 0 + content-addressed cache — identical contract yields identical report.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Rate limiting</td><td>Per-IP sliding window on <code>/analyze</code>.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Access control</td><td>Only the app pages and generated dashboards are served; prompt, source, cache, audit, history are not exposed.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Audit trail</td><td><code>output/audit.log</code> records each run (tokens, cost estimate, warnings) — PII-masked. A per-run log file is also written to <code>output/logs/</code> on every analyze click.</td></tr>
</table>
<p>The subsections below explain <b>how</b> each of the most important controls is actually achieved in the code, not just what it does.</p>

<h2 id="s9a">9.1 Anti-hallucination — how we achieved it</h2>
<p>Hallucination (the model stating something the contract does not) is the single biggest risk for a tool like this, so it is defended in layers — first by instruction, then by verification in code, so that even if the model slips, the output is corrected before the user ever sees it.</p>
<p><b>1 · Grounding by instruction.</b> The prompt's General Rules require the model to use <i>only</i> the uploaded contract, to write <code>"Not stated in uploaded contract"</code> (or <code>null</code>) for anything missing, and to never invent parties, dates, money, penalties, caps or clauses. It must copy names, dates and amounts verbatim, and prefer a lower confidence score over a confident guess. This removes the model's incentive to "fill in the blanks."</p>
<p><b>2 · Evidence for every finding.</b> Each risk row must carry a short, <i>verbatim</i> quote from the contract in its <code>evidence</code> field, plus a <code>confidence</code> score. A claim with no locatable source text is visible immediately, and the grounding check (below) flags any High-risk row that lacks evidence.</p>
<p><b>3 · Deterministic re-computation of the numbers that matter.</b> The figures a manager reads are never trusted from the model — they are recomputed in code by <code>buildHtml.js</code>. Risk counts (High/Medium/Low) are recounted from the actual rows; the "# High Risks" and "Total Risks" KPIs and the chart are derived from those recounts. If no numeric contract value was extracted, any monetary "value at risk" the model produced is <b>nulled</b> and the page renders "Contract value not stated" rather than a fabricated number.</p>
<p><b>4 · Deterministic page numbers.</b> Rather than trust the model's page references, <code>guardrails.reconcilePages()</code> splits the page-marked source text on the <code>[[PAGE n]]</code> markers and re-locates each row's evidence quote in that text, setting <code>pageNo</code> to the page where the quote actually appears. A quote that cannot be found becomes "Not available" — never a wrong page.</p>
<p><b>5 · Output validation with a corrective retry.</b> <code>guardrails.validateOutput()</code> checks the JSON shape and the controlled vocabularies (risk ∈ High/Medium/Low, priority ∈ P1–P4, overall, and the management decision enum). If the first response is malformed or off-schema, <code>analyze.js</code> sends one corrective retry describing the problem before accepting or failing gracefully.</p>
<p><b>6 · Grounding warnings.</b> <code>guardrails.groundingChecks()</code> looks for tell-tale signs of drift — counts that disagree with the rows, money present without a stated value, a negative contract value, end-date before start-date, out-of-range confidence, or a High-risk row with no evidence — and records them to the audit log and the run's warnings for QA.</p>
<p><b>7 · Determinism.</b> The model runs at <b>temperature 0</b>, and every analysis is cached by a hash of the contract text plus the prompt, so the same contract always produces the same report (see 9.3). This makes any hallucination reproducible — and therefore fixable — rather than a moving target.</p>

<h2 id="s9b">9.2 Prompt-injection &amp; jailbreak defense — how we achieved it</h2>
<p>Because the tool feeds an untrusted document straight into an LLM, a contract could contain hidden instructions ("ignore previous instructions", "reveal your system prompt"). The defense is layered so no single trick can subvert it.</p>
<p><b>Untrusted-data framing.</b> The contract is never concatenated into the instructions. <code>guardrails.wrapContract()</code> encloses it in explicit <code>&lt;&lt;&lt;CONTRACT&gt;&gt;&gt; … &lt;&lt;&lt;END CONTRACT&gt;&gt;&gt;</code> markers, and a high-priority hardening block (<code>guardrails.SYSTEM_HARDENING</code>, appended to the system prompt at run time by <code>analyze.js</code>) states that everything between those markers is data to be analyzed, quoted or summarized — <i>never obeyed</i> — and that the instructions must never be revealed or modified.</p>
<p><b>Detection and logging (not blocking).</b> <code>guardrails.detectInjection()</code> scans the text against a set of jailbreak signatures (e.g. "ignore previous instructions", "developer mode", "act as", role tags). It deliberately does <i>not</i> block — a real contract may legitimately quote such phrases — but records a <code>injection_flagged</code> audit event so the run is traceable. The hardening + delimiters neutralize any effect regardless.</p>
<p><b>File-name sanitization.</b> The uploaded file name is also untrusted, so before it is embedded in the prompt <code>analyze.js</code> strips quotes, brackets and newlines and caps its length; the real name is re-applied to the output in code afterward.</p>

<h2 id="s9c">9.3 Determinism &amp; reproducibility — how we achieved it</h2>
<p><b>Temperature 0 + content-addressed cache.</b> The model is called at temperature 0, and <code>analyze.js</code> keys a persistent cache on <code>sha256(contractText + prompt)</code>. An identical contract reuses the exact stored result, so risk counts and the decision never drift between runs. The cache lives in <code>cache/</code>, deliberately <i>separate</i> from <code>output/</code>, so clearing generated dashboards, history or the audit log does not change results (and <code>DISABLE_CACHE=1</code> turns it off for testing).</p>
<p><b>Self-healing cache.</b> A cached result is reused only if it still passes the consistency checks; an older entry with, say, an EM/pricing conflict is discarded so the corrected logic re-runs.</p>
<p><b>Content de-duplication.</b> <code>server.js</code> fingerprints the extracted text (whitespace-normalized SHA-256) and, before spending any tokens, checks history: the same document — even renamed — is not re-analyzed; the user is pointed to the existing report. A same-name-different-content upload is caught too.</p>
<p><b>Resilience.</b> Long analyses auto-continue until the JSON object is complete (<code>completeJson</code>), and transient API errors (timeouts, 429, 5xx) are retried with exponential backoff (<code>withRetry</code>), so a large contract or a blip does not corrupt the output.</p>

<h2 id="s9d">9.4 EM ↔ pricing consistency — how we achieved it</h2>
<p>An engagement-model that contradicts the pricing model (for example Time &amp; Materials shown as "EM 4 – Fixed Price") would undermine trust instantly. This is enforced three times over. The prompt states the valid mapping; <code>guardrails.consistencyChecks()</code> detects any contradiction and triggers a corrective retry (and disqualifies an inconsistent cache entry); and finally <code>buildHtml.js</code> reconciles deterministically — <b>trusting the EM classification and correcting the pricing label to match</b> — so an impossible pair can never reach the screen, with the adjustment noted in the pricing detail.</p>

<h2 id="s9e">9.5 Data protection &amp; privacy — how we achieved it</h2>
<p><b>No file retention.</b> Uploads are written to a temporary folder and deleted immediately after processing (success or failure); only the generated dashboard is kept.</p>
<p><b>PII / secret masking.</b> Everything written to logs or the audit trail passes through <code>guardrails.maskPII()</code>, which redacts emails, phone numbers, Indian PAN, Aadhaar, US SSN, medical record numbers, API keys, cloud keys and passwords — so sensitive values never land in a log file.</p>
<p><b>PHI screening (above &amp; beyond).</b> Because this analyzes contracts, not patient records, <code>guardrails.detectPHI()</code> scans every upload for patient identifiers (MRN, DOB, SSN, ICD codes, health-insurance claim/beneficiary IDs, NPI). Any hit is raised as a run warning, written as a <code>phi_flagged</code> audit event, and surfaced in the dashboard's Limitations legend — so no real patient data can slip in unnoticed.</p>
<p><b>Access control.</b> The server does not expose the project folder. Only <code>index.html</code>, <code>analysis-history.html</code> and generated <code>/output/*.html</code> files are served (with path-traversal and non-HTML requests rejected); the prompt, source, <code>cache/</code>, <code>audit.log</code> and <code>history.json</code> are never reachable over HTTP. The framework version header is disabled.</p>
<p><b>Secret hygiene.</b> The API key lives only in a git-ignored <code>.env</code>; <code>.env.example</code> is the committed placeholder, and <code>.gitignore</code> also excludes <code>node_modules/</code>, <code>output/</code> and <code>cache/</code>.</p>

<h2 id="s9f">9.6 Robustness &amp; abuse controls — how we achieved it</h2>
<p><b>Input validation.</b> <code>guardrails.validateUpload()</code> and Multer's file filter accept only <code>.pdf</code>/<code>.docx</code> up to 25 MB and reject long, path-traversing or control-character file names; <code>validateContractText()</code> rejects empty or scanned (image-only) documents with guidance to run OCR, and caps the text sent to the model.</p>
<p><b>Rate limiting.</b> <code>server.js</code> applies a per-IP sliding window to <code>/analyze</code> (default 20 requests/minute), returning HTTP 429 and logging <code>rate_limited</code> — protecting against runaway cost and abuse.</p>
<p><b>Safe failure &amp; auditability.</b> All errors return a clean message (never a stack trace), logging must never break a request, and every run — success, duplicate, warning, injection/PHI flag, or error — is recorded as a PII-masked JSON line in <code>output/audit.log</code>.</p>

